    "finalTextLength": 1758,
    "finalText": "Teams messages from this past week surfaced a few actual worries — not just routine updates:\n\n- There’s ongoing concern about the Eye Surgeons of Indiana project, especially its early-stage risks:\n    - The lack of a formal budget and contract is creating unease, since decisions are still being made off concept-level estimates.\n    - Multiple messages flagged that landlord approval on layout is a bottleneck and could push out timelines.\n    - Uncertainty around site selection and whether demolition scope will balloon once initial plans are finalized.\n\n- On operational priorities, there is noticeable stress about commitment follow-through:\n    - Teams discussions mention owners and engineers not providing timely feedback, which is slowing down commitments for pending scope.\n    - There's repeated mention that procurement timelines are in danger of slipping — people are pushing for faster decisions on vendors to prevent critical path delays.\n\n- A pattern across projects: fatigue over action items that keep rolling forward with no owner stepping up to close. Field staff vented (in DMs and channels) that recurring meeting action items are stacking up, not getting burned down, which is fueling anxiety about future punchlist and closeout burdens.\n\nNothing in the Teams messages flagged a blow-up or immediate crisis, but the anxiety is real: slow owner decisions, procurement stuck in limbo, and action items without a clear closer. If not addressed, these will become project-level headaches.\n\nNext step: Assign clear owners and dates to any rolling action items, and press for expedited owner/landlord decisions on early-phase projects like Eye Surgeons of Indiana. If you want a breakdown by project or individual, specify, and I’ll pull it."
  },
